---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Ed Barlow — Ed Barlow">
  <section class="home-intro">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h1 class="home-name">Ed Barlow</h1>
      <div class="home-body">
<p>Senior Principal Engineer with 30 years building enterprise platforms at hedge funds,
health systems, and startups. Now applying that foundation to <strong>AI-assisted software development.</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>I help small and mid-sized businesses adopt AI development practices</strong> — not just tools,
but the workflow, governance, and project structure that makes AI actually deliver.</p>
</blockquote>
<h2>The Framework</h2>
<p>Most teams get AI wrong. They add a coding assistant but keep the same chaotic workflow.
The result: faster generation of the same mess. My approach is different.</p>
<p>I bring a structured framework — GAME (Generic Agent Management Environment) — that gives
every project a standard shape: defined stack, governed operations, observable processes,
and AI prompts tuned to each development stage.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Structured Workflow</strong> — features move through a defined lifecycle from Idea to Done,
  with Agent Assist at each gate</li>
<li><strong>Governed Operations</strong> — every project's start, stop, test, and deploy scripts are
  registered automatically and run from a single dashboard</li>
<li><strong>Observable by Default</strong> — heartbeats, process logs, and usage analytics built in
  from day one</li>
<li><strong>Markdown as Configuration</strong> — your stack rules, project metadata, and Claude
  instructions live in plain text files you own and version</li>
</ul>
<p><a href="/webcloudstudio/diagrams/architecture.png">View the system architecture →</a></p>
<h2>How It Works</h2>
<p>A new project gets a standard shape on day one: a <code>CLAUDE.md</code> that tells the AI assistant
exactly how to work in this codebase, a <code>STACK.yaml</code> that declares technology rules, and
<code>bin/</code> scripts with headers that self-register as UI buttons. The AI knows the conventions.
You don't repeat yourself.</p>
<p><a href="/webcloudstudio/diagrams/feature-workflow.png">See the feature development lifecycle →</a></p>
<p><a href="/webcloudstudio/diagrams/bin-integration.png">See how bin/ scripts integrate with the platform →</a></p>
<h2>Engagements</h2>
<p>I work with teams who are serious about building well, not just building fast.
Typical engagements: platform setup and methodology, AI-assisted sprint acceleration,
architecture review, and hands-on development.</p>
<p><em>Reach out via the Contact link above.</em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    .home-intro { padding: 4rem 0 3rem; }

    .home-name {
      font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 5vw, 4rem);
      font-weight: 800;
      letter-spacing: -0.02em;
      margin: 0 0 2rem;
    }

    .home-body { max-width: 680px; }

    .home-body p {
      font-size: 1.05rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      line-height: 1.75;
      margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
    }

    .home-body h2 {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: var(--text);
      margin: 2rem 0 0.75rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.01em;
    }

    .home-body ul {
      list-style: none;
      padding: 0;
      margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 0.5rem;
    }

    .home-body li {
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      padding-left: 1.2rem;
      position: relative;
    }

    .home-body li::before {
      content: '—';
      position: absolute;
      left: 0;
      color: var(--accent);
    }

    .home-body strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }

    .home-body em {
      color: var(--muted);
      font-style: italic;
      font-size: 0.92rem;
    }
  </style>
</Layout>
